\begin{q}[5pts.\ extra credit]
  In class, we saw the following two part theorem:
  \begin{itemize}
  \item If $ g $ is continuous at $ a $ and $ f $ is
    continuous at $ g(a) $, then $$ \lim_{x \to a} f(g(x)) =
    f( \lim_{x \to a} g(x) ) $$.
  \item \item If $ \lim_{x \to a} g(x)= L $ and $ f $ is
    continuous at $ L $, then $$ \lim_{x \to a} f(g(x)) =
    f( \lim_{x \to a} g(x) ) $$.
  \end{itemize}
  Which of these two statements is more general than the
  other and why?
\end{q}

